First of all, we load required libraries for data importing (Quandl and gtrendsR) for measure values and Google Trends values (max is stretched to 100, min is stretched to 0). I also include quantmod to use chartSeries plots.

I choose gold prices (GOLD), oil prices (OIL) and Microsoft share prices(MSFT) as my 3 measures.

Some data manipulation (year ordering) and assignments are below.

library(Quandl)
library(quantmod)
library(gtrendsR)
Quandl.api_key("27uxjqL9o-tRDCUy_wxS")


# Measures of Interest by Quandl package
MSFT <- Quandl("EOD/MSFT", type = "xts")
head(MSFT)
OIL <- Quandl("OPEC/ORB", type = "xts")
head(OIL)
GOLD <- Quandl("LBMA/GOLD", type = "xts")
head(GOLD)


# Google Trends Data with gtrendsR package
GOLD_GTRENDS <- gtrends(keyword = "GOLD", time = "2018-01-01 2020-11-18")
GOLD_GTRENDS_interest <- xts(GOLD_GTRENDS$interest_over_time$hits, order.by = GOLD_GTRENDS$interest_over_time$date)
colnames(GOLD_GTRENDS_interest) <- c("GOLD_hits")
GOLD_GTRENDS_interest <- GOLD_GTRENDS_interest[nrow(GOLD_GTRENDS_interest):1]
OIL_GTRENDS <- gtrends(keyword = "OIL", time = "2018-01-01 2020-11-18")
OIL_GTRENDS_interest <- xts(OIL_GTRENDS$interest_over_time$hits, order.by = OIL_GTRENDS$interest_over_time$date)
colnames(OIL_GTRENDS_interest) <- c("OIL_hits")
OIL_GTRENDS_interest <- OIL_GTRENDS_interest[nrow(OIL_GTRENDS_interest):1]
MSFT_GTRENDS <- gtrends(keyword = "MSFT", time = "2015-01-01 2017-12-28")
MSFT_GTRENDS_interest <- xts(MSFT_GTRENDS$interest_over_time$hits, order.by = MSFT_GTRENDS$interest_over_time$date)
colnames(MSFT_GTRENDS_interest) <- c("MSFT_hits")
MSFT_GTRENDS_interest <- MSFT_GTRENDS_interest[nrow(MSFT_GTRENDS_interest):1]

We use to.yearly to find the timestamps for year ends. I only used 3 years for each measures. Additional years can be done in the same way. For ease, each year ebd are assigned to relative objects.

GOLD_end_2020 <- which(index(GOLD)=="2020-11-18")
GOLD_end_2019 <- which(index(GOLD)=="2019-12-31")
GOLD_end_2018 <- which(index(GOLD)=="2018-12-31")

Gold plots:

# GOLD plots
par(mfrow = c(1,1))
chartSeries(GOLD[,1], main= "GOLD")

plot(to.yearly(GOLD[,1])[,4], main = "GOLD")

hist(to.yearly(GOLD[,1])[,4], breaks = 25, main = "GOLD")

par(mfrow = c(3,1))
plot(GOLD[(GOLD_end_2019+1):GOLD_end_2020, 1], main = "GOLD-2020")
plot(GOLD[(GOLD_end_2018+1):GOLD_end_2019, 1], main = "GOLD-2019")
plot(GOLD[(GOLD_end_2017+1):GOLD_end_2018, 1], main = "GOLD-2018")

par(mfrow = c(3,1))
hist(GOLD[(GOLD_end_2019+1):GOLD_end_2020, 1], breaks = 25, main = "GOLD-2020")
hist(GOLD[(GOLD_end_2018+1):GOLD_end_2019, 1], breaks = 25, main = "GOLD-2019")
hist(GOLD[(GOLD_end_2017+1):GOLD_end_2018, 1], breaks = 25, main = "GOLD-2018")

2018 differs from 2019 and 2020 in overall shape. There are several reasons that affect the gold prices in those times and the difference may result from them. Additionally, histograms show some similarity regarding frequency distributions. However, 2020 slightly diverges from other years as global uncertainties and tensions rose with regional conflicts and Covid-19.

Oil Plots:

# OIL plots
par(mfrow = c(1,1))
chartSeries(OIL[,1], main = "OIL")

plot(to.yearly(OIL[,1])[,4], main = "OIL")

hist(to.yearly(OIL[,1])[,4], breaks = 25, main = "OIL")

par(mfrow = c(3,1))
plot(OIL[(OIL_end_2019+1):OIL_end_2020, 1], main = "OIL-2020")
plot(OIL[(OIL_end_2018+1):OIL_end_2019, 1], main = "OIL-2019")
plot(OIL[(OIL_end_2017+1):OIL_end_2018, 1], main = "OIL-2018")

par(mfrow = c(3,1))
hist(GOLD[(OIL_end_2019+1):OIL_end_2020, 1], breaks = 25, main = "OIL-2020")
hist(GOLD[(OIL_end_2018+1):OIL_end_2019, 1], breaks = 25, main = "OIL-2019")
hist(GOLD[(OIL_end_2017+1):OIL_end_2018, 1], breaks = 25, main = "OIL-2018")

Oil price movements are divergent. The volatility and signs of changes differ significantly. However, histograms of frequency distributions are similar to a certain degree. The movements over one whole year show similar distribution patterns despite happening in different time intervals in each year.

Microsofts both price change and frequency plots show great similarities. Microsoft is more stable and consistent throughout years, even if the value per share increases every year.

Gold boxplots:

par(mfrow = c(1,3))
boxplot(as.data.frame(to.weekly(GOLD[(GOLD_end_2019+1):GOLD_end_2020, 1])[,4]), ylim = c(1200,2050), main = "GOLD_2020")
boxplot(as.data.frame(to.weekly(GOLD[(GOLD_end_2018+1):GOLD_end_2019, 1])[,4]), ylim = c(1200,2100), main = "GOLD_2019")
boxplot(as.data.frame(to.weekly(GOLD[(GOLD_end_2017+1):GOLD_end_2018, 1])[,4]), ylim = c(1200,2100), main = "GOLD_2018")

# index(GOLD_GTRENDS_interest)[1]
# index(GOLD_GTRENDS_interest)[53]
# index(GOLD_GTRENDS_interest)[105]

par(mfrow = c(1,3))
boxplot(as.data.frame(GOLD_GTRENDS_interest[1:52]), ylim = c(50,100)                           , main = "GOLD_GTRENDS_2020")
boxplot(as.data.frame(GOLD_GTRENDS_interest[53:104]), ylim = c(50,100)                         , main = "GOLD_GTRENDS_2019")
boxplot(as.data.frame(GOLD_GTRENDS_interest[105:nrow(GOLD_GTRENDS_interest)]), ylim = c(50,100), main = "GOLD_GTRENDS_2018")

As gold prices rises and range of prices increases, strangely number of searches of the word gold decreases. This clearly shows the increasing gold prices reversely affect individuals interest. Maybe, volatility in these prices interests more people than the overall price levels.

Microsoft boxplots:

par(mfrow = c(1,3))
boxplot(as.data.frame(to.weekly(MSFT[(MSFT_end_2016+1):MSFT_end_2017, 1])[,4]), ylim = c(40,85), main = "MSFT_2017")

# index(MSFT_GTRENDS_interest)[1]
# index(MSFT_GTRENDS_interest)[53]
# index(MSFT_GTRENDS_interest)[105]

par(mfrow = c(1,3))
boxplot(as.data.frame(MSFT_GTRENDS_interest[1:52]), ylim = c(20,65)                           , main = "MSFT_GTRENDS_2017")
boxplot(as.data.frame(MSFT_GTRENDS_interest[53:104]), ylim = c(20,65)                         , main = "MSFT_GTRENDS_2016")
boxplot(as.data.frame(MSFT_GTRENDS_interest[105:nrow(MSFT_GTRENDS_interest)]), ylim = c(20,65), main = "MSFT_GTRENDS_2015")

Again, despite the increase in prices and volatility, people showed less or same level of interest on Microsoft. It is again interesting to see this pattern, remembering Microsoft being a tech company and holding huge share in technology area. This may again be a result of Microsofts low key policy until around 2017 with only providing software products that have constant non-changing use in life. For 2018 and onwards, the pattern might have changed due to Microsofts moves in hardware department and interesting developments that attracted many people.
